# Svelte 5 Runes

Compose is on Svelte 5. Use runes exclusively — no legacy reactive statements
(`$:`), no legacy `export let` props, no old-style stores.

## Props

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import type { Note } from '$lib/types';

  interface Props {
    note: Note;
    showAuthor?: boolean;
    onarchive?: (id: string) => void;
  }

  let { note, showAuthor = false, onarchive }: Props = $props();
</script>
```

- Props come from `$props()` and are typed via an explicit `Props` interface.
- Default values go in the destructure, not as `defineProps` defaults.
- Callback props use the `on<event>` name pattern (e.g., `onarchive`, not `onArchive`).

## State

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  let count = $state(0);
  let items = $state<string[]>([]);
  let user = $state<{ name: string; role: 'admin' | 'member' } | null>(null);
</script>
```

- Primitives: `$state(value)` creates a reactive cell.
- Collections: `$state([])` or `$state({})` — mutations in-place are tracked.
- Re-assignment is also tracked.

## Derived values

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  let notes = $state<Note[]>([]);
  let archived = $derived(notes.filter((n) => n.archivedAt !== null));
  let unarchived = $derived(notes.filter((n) => n.archivedAt === null));
</script>
```

- `$derived(expr)` recomputes when any reactive dep inside `expr` changes.
- Never assign to a `$derived` — it's read-only.
- Never reach outside runes to trigger updates; the compiler tracks deps automatically.

## Effects

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  let count = $state(0);

  $effect(() => {
    document.title = `Count: ${count}`;
  });

  $effect(() => {
    const id = setInterval(() => { count++; }, 1000);
    return () => clearInterval(id);
  });
</script>
```

- Use `$effect` only for side effects (DOM APIs, timers, external subscriptions)
- Return a cleanup function for anything that allocates
- Never use `$effect` to derive state — use `$derived`

## Binding

Two-way with `bind:`:

```svelte
<input bind:value={name} />
<input type="checkbox" bind:checked={agreed} />
```

For custom components, declare a writable prop with `bindable`:

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  let { value = $bindable(''), onchange }: { value?: string; onchange?: (v: string) => void } = $props();
</script>
```

## Don't

- Don't use `$:` reactive statements — Svelte 5 still parses them but they're deprecated and don't compose with runes
- Don't use `export let` — use `$props()`
- Don't use `writable()` / `readable()` / `derived()` from `svelte/store` — use runes
- Don't mix Options-style component definitions with `<script setup>` — Svelte has no such concept, just use the rune API
